%N A393124 The smallest non-palindromic number greater than n whose digit reversals in base n and base n+1, when read as a number in those bases, are equal.
%C A393124 Starting from base 10 it appears that every third term is significantly less than the two terms in between.
%C A393124 Note that if palindromes are allowed then the sequence appears to be the same as A048268 except for the first term, which would equal 47 instead of 6643.
%H A393124 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A393124/b393124.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..64</a>
%e A393124 a(2) = 47 as 47 = 101111_2 = 1202_3 which have digit reversals 111101_2 = 61 and 2021_3 = 61, where 101111_2 is not a palindrome and both digit reversals equal 61.
%e A393124 a(10) = 30043 as 30043 = 30043_10 = 20632_11 which have digit reversals 34003_10 = 34003 and 23602_11 = 34003, where 30043_10 is not a palindrome and both digit reversals equal 34003.
%t A393124 a[n_]:=Module[{k=n+1}, While[PalindromeQ[IntegerDigits[k,n]]||IntegerReverse[k,n]!=IntegerReverse[k,n+1],k++];k];Array[a,9,2] (* _James C. McMahon_, Mar 05 2026 *)
%Y A393124 Cf. A004086, A029742, A393720, A393721, A393902, A393903, A048268.
%K A393124 nonn,base,new
%O A393124 2,1
